column69: Laborers from Applied Aquatic supervised by Dallas Holmes were treating Brazilian pepper along the north side of I-75 near the parallel canal on May 31, 2017. At approximately 3:05pm laborers spotted the 8-10? python which was startled and retreated into a fallen, hollowed out, sabal palm trunk where it started to coil around its eggs. The laborers pulled the snake out of the trunk by its tail and dispatched it. Dallas called me, Ryan Brown, and asked for instructions. I instructed him to count the eggs, destroy them, and to send me a location. Dallas sent these pictures of before and after the eggs were destroyed. Only 8 eggs were located inside of the sabal trunk. The location of the clutch is attached.

column2: Jesse Blanchard Florida International University
column69: It was on the south side of 8th street, approximately 15 minutes from the Big Cypress Oasis visitor center, near mile marker 39. No cell signal or GPS on hand for precise location.
column153: The specimen was found on the South side of the road, presumably struck by a car behind the head as the bones there were out of alignment. Unfortunately there was no cell service and I didn't have a GPS on hand so the location is a rough estimate.These pictures were taken around 8:15am. No decomposition was noted and no scavengers had found the carcass yet so time of death was likely close to that time. I reported the find to Kelly Gestring as soon as I was able to get service and he forwarded the report on to relevant persons. I drove back by the area around 12pm and it was gone so this specimen may have been retrieved.

column69: The end of Stromboli Drive on Snake Creek in Venetian Shores, Mile Marker 86 on US1 in the Village of Islamorada.
column153: The snake was sighted three times:02/10/2016, 02/29/2016 and  03/6/2016. The snake was seen the first time entering the water of the canal between Giardino Drive and Stromboli Drive; the second time it was seen sunning itself on the asphalt of Stromboli Drive at the end of the street; the third time it was seen swimming in the same canal opposite where it hd entered the water at the first sighting. It was described as about 10-12 feet in length and very thick. Since being sighted, the local iguana population seems to have disappeared after expanding to the nuisance level and a great blue heron that used to feed from our dock every evening has also disappeared. I may be reached at cooper.keys@gmail.com or 305-664-3072 in case of need. Thank you.John C. Cooper152 Giardino DriveIslamorada, FL 33036-3312

column153: A Burmese python approximately 10 feet long was spotted while a contractor was working onsite.  Unfortunately, the snake moved before any photos could be taken and before capturing or killing it could be attempted.  It wasn't spotted again afterwards.  Russell Hunt, the biologist for FPL's Everglades Mitigation Bank, made this report but the sighting was made by Louie Carricarte, a contractor onsite.  The sighting was made near 12:30PM on Friday, February 19, 2016.

column2: Lelon Carroll U.S. Army Retired
column69: In Holmes Creek, approximately 400 yards from the entrance of the Choctawhatchee River. The Burmese Python was laying on a log and disappeared into the water after I came up alongside it on my boat. I recognized the brown camo pattern of the snake and it was too large to be anything else indigenous to the area.
column153: I did not have a camera with me at the time. Spotting was last Spring (May 2014). I didn't know you could report it online until I found this website. I estimate that the snake was approximately 14 foot in length (almost the length of my Bass Tracker Fishing Boat which is 17 1/2 foot long.  It had a thick circumference, at least the circumference of a human thigh. I notified a couple of people in my community (River Ranch Retreat) of the sighting. They noted that the County Commissioner while boating close to the location I reported seeing it, a year or so before my sighting, he (Charles Brock - District 2) had also seen such a size snake (near the 'Knot Hole' on the Choctawhatchee River. This is about 1 mile from my sighting.

column153: Python crossing rd. It froze when I parked in front of it with headlights shining on it. I took pictues and then a car drove over it. It then slithered off. It came from what we call "the north side" of Collier Seminole State Park, which is wet pine flatwoods with some scrubby and mesic pine flatwoods. It is the 6.5 mile trail entrance to the park. It went across the road to a saltmarsh, that is mainly fresh this time of year.

column69: Naples, Clam Pass Park unspecified location along the boardwalk
column153: In February, 2011 my family saw a very large snake with a very large girth. Could not see the entire length. At the time I did not know the species, but this year, 2014, on a ENP mangrove tour I asked the naturalist what he thought the snake might be and he answered a Burmese Python. The snake was transferring itself from beneath the boardwalk onto Mangrove trees. I cannot say what it was, except that it was large around and very heavy as we saw the tree branch bend under it's weight. If it was a python I thought to let you know as it was in the midst of a residential area. Sorry this is so late but we only visit Florida for a shore time each year.

column69: Everglades National Park, NW side of Clive Key
column153: I was on the North West side of Clive Key doing spoonbill research, and under a black mangrove tree half in the salt-wart,(batis?) I saw a really fat Burmese Python. it was probably somewhere around 10-12 feet long and maybe a foot thick at the thickest part. It was around 11:15 am and the snake seemed to be resting in the shade until we came along. As we approached it went off under the salt wart foliage. it was seen not too far from bird nesting in between the red mangrove coast and the prairie to the interior of the island. I marked the tree (black mangrove)that it was under with 3 blue flags, the center flag has written in sharpie "Big Python."

column153: Bank of culvert pond (almost like a man-made gator hole) on the northern side of the canal. Encountered around noon, temperature 28 degrees Celsius, partly cloudy. Alligator sunning on a bank of culvert pond had object in mouth. When alligator retreated to the water, we saw that it had a burmese python. It abandoned its food item for our photo documentation. Python has been identified as a male, measuring approximately 2.75m.

column153: Dead python floating on north side of canal on SW328th St, about midway between flashing light at SW 117th Ave and Biscayne National Park entrance. Python was measured as 2.8 m long (total length, not SVL). Snake appeared fresh dead, had some bloating but was not rigid, and with no obviously apparent cause of death. Snake was removed from canal (where it was very obvious and might likely be reported again) and dragged into the vegetation alongside the canal. GPS point indicates final disposition location.

column69: Key Largo, SE Marlin Ave 50 m E of US-1
column153: Observation of what seemed likely to be a Burmese python was found in search of MCSO Dispatcher's Logs: Saturday. February 6. 2010 15:25 COWART, RYAN 9182 MCS010CAD013751 1 MARLIN AVE SOUTH KEY LARGO, MARLIN AVE SOUTH 103.4 OC - SYLVESTRI, JR. (305) 522-2385 I interviewed Joseph R Silvestri on 23 Sep 2013. A home construction contractor, Silvestri lives on SE Marlin Avenue, in Largo Sound Park subdivision (mile marker 103.3). Leaving home to go to a worksite, he noticed a crowd gathering at a new residence he was building at #1 SE Marlin Avenue. Stopping, he asked why they were on his lot, and was told some of them has watched a very large snake disappear into a pile of boulders he had on the site. Using a backhoe he had parked there, he removed boulders from the pile until he saw enough of the snake to identifiy it as a python. He then called the MCSO non-emergency line to report it, and waited until FWC officers arrived and captured the python. FWC officers told Silvestri privately that they would euthanize the snake once they had it away from the public eye. The snake was not measured before it was taken away, but Silvestri said that an article in a local paper the following week mentioned that the snake was a 9 feet 6 inches long Burmese python. One of the officers says the snake is 8'10" in the video (Larry Connor, FWCC, personal communication). See this photo voucher (video) on YouTube: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=snbXJOG1h0U

column153: Small (150 cm) Burmese python dead-on-road in US Route 1 (State Road 5) right-of-way, as reported one day earlier by Crocodile Lake Wildlife Refuge Manager Jeremy Dixon. I was able to confirm python reported 10-Aug-2013 (11:28 AM) as described: on southbound side of and close to concrete lane divider, just a couple of miles south of Miami-Dade County line. As of July 15, 2013 we've been asked by FDOT contractor monitoring wildlife mortailty between US Route 1 MM 106.5 and US Route 1 MM 128 DOR specimens we NOT remove road kill or push it to the side unless it has been spray painted. Part of what they are contracted to do is count the number of road-killed wildlife each week. They conduct their counts on Thursday or Friday so generally throughout the week we should remove not anything from the road. Garmin eTrex 10 (WGS 84) using WAAS/EGNOS w/GPS + GLONASS,+/- 2 meters

column2: Gary Brumit
column69: Private paved road crossing over 3 culverts where water drains into canal/lake
column153: Snake looked to appear at least 10 feet long, we have a one lane private road and the snake was moving across the road as I was cutting grass on edge of road. As it was moving across road it was almost as long as the road is wide. It had dark blotched pattern on full length of body with a lighter tan separating the dark blotched patterns. Diameter body of snake was close to size of my calf, I am 52, 5'9, 190 lbs ( to give you an idea of my size ), underneath body appeared to be white in color with speckled pattern running along bottom edge. The zero turn mower I was on must have scared it and it was moving from lake area where there is a heavy under brush growth canal. It crossed the road opposite side of lake in a heavy under brush empty lot beside my fathers house. I did not get pictures since I was on mower cutting grass and the snake was moving rapidly away from the sound of mower I assume and disappeared into brush. I know what I saw, it definitely wasn't a rattle snake, when I viewed the web site here I immediately identified the snake being a Burmese Python. You are more than welcome to call me anytime, I have a trail cam setup in the area in hoping to cath it on camera for you.

column153: Observed the snake in the bayou swimming next to the mangroves adjacent to the Vinoy Golf Course and just to the NW of 990 Bayview Place NE. We could see at least 8 feet of the snake and the rest was under water. My son and I were in his Gheenoe fishing about noon on Monday and had just anchored when he spotted it just behind the boat and took the picture with his phone. That is the only photo we got because the snake was spooked and took off to the north. There is a tidal ditch to the north that runs further to the west which is parallel to the south side of 31st Terrace NE that leads to a golf course lake down by 3090 Walnut Street NE. The north side of the ditch is homes but the south side is the golf course.  I wonder if it is living in there?

column27: Jason Leon, personal communicaton
column69: Miami-Dade County, Tennessee Rd (SW 167th Ave) appx 690 m N of Card Sound Rd
column153: Jason Leon of Miami was driving on Tennessee Rd/SW 167th Ave south of SW 360th St on Saturday, May 11. At about 23:00, he and his passenger sighted a large Burmese python sticking about three feet out from the brush. He stopped the car, grabbed the snake behind the head and tried to drag it out. The snake began to wrap around his leg so he called for assistance from some people who recreating with him, got a knife, and decapitated the snake. On Monday, he called the FWC WPB Regional office and was forwarded to our Exotic Species Hotline. Cheryl Millet from TNC took the call and gathered initial information. Jeff Fobb from Miami-Dade Fire Rescue arranged to have one of his co-workers pick up the snake from Mr. Leon on Monday evening. Joy Vinci from UF picked up the snake from Jeff Fobb on Tuesday. UF performed a necropsy Wednesday, May 15.    Length: 18? 8", Weight: 128.26 lbs, Female, Empty stomach, Small, unidentified feather in lower GI tract, No eggs, No microchip.

column69: Charlton County, River Rd appx 1.63 km S of Winokur Rd
column153: Sighting reported from a news article: Published: 11/09 4:36 pm Updated: 11/09 6:58 pm FOLKSTON, Ga. -- Charles O'Qinn and Terry Lee have seen many things cross River Road, but they never thought a python would be one of them. "We didn't really know what kind of snake it was. We just knew it was a big one," said Lee. They spotted half of it slithering across the rural road Monday. They followed it into the brush and shot it. "If it got a hold of a grown man, he wouldn't have a chance. He was too strong. I couldn't even hold it by the tail," said O'Qinn. The pair said the snake was at least 11-foot long and more than a foot around. "He was real fat. So he has been eating," said O'Qinn. "They are getting everywhere in South Florida, and they could be up here too," said Lee. The python was just outside of the Okefenokee Swamp, but researchers don't think that's where it originated. "Pythons can get large enough to eat things like small deer and small children," said UNF Biology professor Joseph Butler. Butler studies reptiles and believes this one was released. "Usually these animals are not going to make it through the winter." "We don't need that type of snake in this area. It's not native," said Lee. The snake's bones are still left laying on the side of River Road. And the pair hopes that is the only thing the python left behind.

column99: South Ocean Shores Drive, Key Largo, FL
column153: The Florida Keys Free Press published a photo and caption under the headline "Another Python" on page 8 of the paper's October 3, 2012 edition. When I reported this record to EDDMaps, the photo and caption were available online at: http://pdf.keysnews.com/weeklys/freepress.pdf Just in case that is no longer the case: The photo shows a man holding the snake by its tail. The man (approximately 5'9" tall, according to Ms. Dillon) has his arm extended upwards at a 45 degree angle, and the snake's head does not quite reach the ground The published estimated length of "almost seven feet" appears reasonable. Below the photo is the following caption: "Key Largo resident Beverly Dillon found an almost 7-foot python in front of her house Thursday, Sept. 28, after workers began clearing a lot across the street from her South Ocean Shores home. 'This great big thing crawled right in front of the street,? Dillon said. ?It was fighting and going nuts.? The workers killed the invasive snake. Officials are beginning to find more and more pythons coming south from Everglades National Park." My October 6 telephone call to the witness cited in the caption (Beverly Dillon) produced additional details. The snake was discovered during routine maintenance / clearing of brush on an overgrown vacant lot on South Ocean Shores Drive, Key Largo, Florida. Employees of the landscape maintenance company killed the python, and took the the carcass away when they left, as requested by residents of the adjacent property. Ms. Dillon also mentioned that residents of another home in the neighborhood reportedly own and breed pythons. The location information is intentionally vague as I am not sure if the snake was on the County-owned right-of-way or the adjacent privately-owned vacant lot. It was on the half of South Ocean Shores Drive that is west of Ocean Bay Drive, Key Largo, Florida. The owner of the adjacent private lot was not contacted regarding this report, so the location given is intentionally imprecise, and is shown as intersection of South Ocean Shores Drive and Ocean Bay Drive (accurate within 300 meters).  Larry Connor, FWCC, changed the observation date to 9/27/2012 based on image properties of the iPhone image provided by Beverly Dillon.

column69: Key Largo, Pompano Ave appx 280 m W of US-1
column153: This python was first observed moving from south to north across Pompano Avenue, a paved street in a relatively quiet neighborhood - the Bowens Addition to Riviera Village subdivision on Key Largo, approximately 300 meters west (bayside) of U.S. Highway Route 1 (a.k.a. State Road 5) mile marker 105. It moved off the cleared right-of-way, and into cover just inside the margin of hardwood hammock at Block 6, Lots 16, 17 and 18 of Bowens Addition to Riviera Village Subdivision. As a former resident of 38 Pompano Avenue (100 feet from where the snake was observed), I would describe this subdivision as heavily wooded despite being 75% developed, and much less than 75% occupied during August, as many residents leave for the summer. Most of the properties at the west end of the subdivision (west of Bay Drive and on Blackwater Sound) are large and many retain remnants of hardwood hammock. Between Bay Drive and US Route 1, many of the homeowners have retained at least large shade trees, some have kept small remnants of the native forest. There are also many undeveloped lots still covered by dense hardwood hammock, with vines and poisonwood (Metopium toxiferum) often making access less than convenient. Any constrictor, as long as it remained undetected by residents, would find ample prey here as there are many free-roaming domestic cats, as well as resident opossums, raccoons, grey squirrels, and abundant non-native rats (Rattus rattus).  On 30-August-2012, at approximately 11:00 PM, Monroe County Sheriff's Office (MCSO) Deputy Bryan Cross was conducting routine patrols of Key Largo?s residential neighborhoods when he observed a large snake moving from south to north across a Monroe County right-of-way. Estimating the snake's length at 10 feet, Deputy Cross called Florida Fish and Wildlife Conservation Commission (FWC) dispatch for assistance. Responding FWC Officers Jason Rafter, Kip Hoover and Shelton Bartlet were joined by MCSO Sergeant Jason Madnick, and the five officers searched the area until finding the python, at about 11:25 PM, under a brush pile just inside the hardwood hammock of undeveloped lots (across from # 32 Pompano Avenue, Key Largo, FL 33037) and just a few yards from where it had been first observed. The following afternoon (31-Aug-2012), Officer Rafter transferred the live python to United States Geological Survey (USGS) Invasive Species Science biologists James Duquesnel and Michelle McEachern. During the transfer, Duquesnel took several photos (three are attached to this report) of the snake and Officers Rafter and Hoover, assisted by FWC Officer Janet Fernandez, who helped hold the snake for the photo. McEachern then transported the snake to Everglades National Park's Dan Beard Center, where Wildlife Biologist Skip Snow confirmed the species identification, and reported the following after his post-mortem examination: mass: 9,448 grams; snout to vent length: 254 cm; total length: 287 cm (9 ft., 4 in.); girth: 25.4 cm. Both ovaries with numerous small follicles (max dia. 8.0 mm, 7.2, 6.9) Oviducts thin and narrow, not at all thick nor muscular. Virgin female. Stomach empty. Moderate amount of fecal material collected from lower GI (frozen), hair observed and numerous large parasitic worms (70% ETOH). Tail collected (frozen) A few mites and one lungworm also collected (70% ETOH) Carcass retained for FLMNH (frozen). AVID scan negative. Body with a few small old scars. The specimen will most likely be deposited in the collection at Florida Museum of Natural History (Gainesville, FL).

column69: Miami-Dade County, vicinity of MM-26 Krome Ave appx 5.54 km N of US-41
column153: Approximately 12'  python found DOR approx 50 yds south of the MM26 sign Krome Ave. Was hit several times but looked as though it may have been hit in the south bound lane while it was heading east. PyMo_1953, Male, TL 330 cm, SVL 288 cm, tail 42 cm. Badly broked, rolled, and scavanged, yet relatively fresh and in "good" shape. Avid and Biomark scans negative. Stomach empty, small amounts of hair and bird quills scraped from remaining lower gi tract. The few fat bodies observed were small, red, and widely spaced suggesting the animal was underwieight for its size. Tissue saved, carcass discarded (Skip Snow, National Park Service, personal communication).

column153: A hunter by the name of Steve Gagne killed an 18 foot Burmese python on Loop Road (CR94) in Collier County, Saturday March 27, 2010. Location was at the air boat ramp at coordinates N25 45.67, W80 52.56. His phone # 786-412-7874 and he works for Critter Control. He gutted the snake and found nothing in the stomach, the female was in shed. Big Cypress park rangers and Collier S.O. was present. Gagne reported that the young park rangers were upset about saying that they should not remove it from the preserve, but the S.O. officers were glad that he took it. Initial reported location was incorrect. Coordinates changed after talking to M. Peters who captured the snake.

column153: The python collected by hunter Roger Newton from the BICY Stairsteps on 12 Dec 2009 was a mature female Burmese python, 434 cm in total length, with a mass of 33.3 kg. The stomach was empty but enlarged, probably in anticipation of the meal it was in the process of obtaining (snake was in the process of squeezing a great white heron when shot). A very small amount of fecal material was collected from the lower GI tract - a couple of gator scutes were observed (Sikp Snow, Everglades National Park, personal communication).

column69: Collier-Seminole State Park, SR-92 2.0 km W of US-41
column153: Driving north on S.R. 92. Headlights picked up large snake on side of road, by guard railing. Turned back around for a closer look - did not leave vehicle, but shined lights on snake long enough to identify it as a python, roughly 8-10 feet long and estimated 16-18" in diameter at thickest section. Assumed it to be a Burmese Python based on comparing markings to pictures. Snake made a leisurely retreat into forest after 30-45 seconds of observation.

column69: Key Largo, western boundry of Crocodile Lake NWR appx 0.33 km NE of US-1 and CR-905 split
column88: United States Fish and Wildlife service
column153: On 25 September 2009, Ron Rozar, USGS, and crew, caught a Burmese python in a trap on Key Largo. The animal was a male, with a live measured snout-to-vent length of 185 cm, total length of 207 cm, and a mass of 4.014 kg. The animal was caught in an unbaited, round entrance trap located on a drift fence near the western boundary of the Crocodile Lake NWR (~0.33 km NE of the US 1 - CR 905 split). The UTM coordinates of the capture are 563194; 2784405. The body condition of the snake was good, though its disposition left a little to be desired. The animal was necropsied on 28 September. The animal was a male with testes still developing, ducts thin, not thickened, nor convoluted. Stomach was empty. Three small fecal pellets were collected from the lower GI tract. Mike Rochford (UF) and Skip Snow (ENP) confirmed the id of hair, small bone fragments, and a few very small teeth, to be the remains of a black rat (Rattus rattus). Photos were taken and tissue archived (frozen) for genetics, mercury, etc. PyMo_1401.

Stomach was empty, and a moderate amount of fecal material was collected from the lower GI tract, however nothing was immediately identifiable. Contents retained for further examination.

column2: Skip Snow Everglades National Park
column27: Skip Snow, National Park Service, personal communication
column69: Spruce Creek, Kendrew Dr appx 130 m N of Boggs Ford Rd
column153: Observed on a forested private lot behind a residence which is adjacent to a small tributary of Spruce Creek in Port Orange, Volusia Co. Python first seen 2 or 3 Mondays before Thanksgiving. At that time a chainsaw operator stepped on it while cutting some trees on the property. The sawyer recognized it to be a Burmese python because he used to keep them as pets. No one has seen the snake since. The homeowner believes the snake has been eating her free range cats (many of which have gone missing over the last 2 years). Estimated size of the snake was 10'-12' approx. 6" across. No photos available. I provided the home owner with the name and phone number of FWC's Jenny Novak Tinell for further advice and assistance.

column2: Skip Snow Everglades National Park
column25: Florida Museum of Natural History Herpetology Collection
column27: Skip Snow, National Park Service, personal communication
column69: Key Largo, vicinity of Overseas Highway and Francis Drake Dr
column153: At about 1:10 pm on Tuesday, 24 June 2008, the Python Hotline received a call from Sue Nulman, 98610 Overseas Highway (Bayside) Key Largo. Ms. Nulman had found a python on her property in a shaded area attempting to eat one of her "pet" birds, one of many wild doves (and other wildlife) she feeds. The Nulman property appears to be rather large and wooded. At around 12:30 pm she saw the python, mostly concealed by leaves, with a dove, dead but not swallowed. Nulman stunned the snake with a blow to the head and then severed the spinal cord. I was in the area so stopped to pick up the carcass, and chat. She expressed concern about the remaining wildlife and the dog, and how to secure the house against pythons. Nulman got the Python Hotline number from a flyer she picked up in Big Cypress. I took the carcass back to the lab and performed a necropsy late in the afternoon. Results are as follows: PyMo_901, a male, some rigor in the carcass, 207.5 cm (TL), 181.0 cm (SVL), with a mass of 3.972 kg and a girth of 18.5 cm. Looks to be near mature, perhaps breeding for the first time this coming winter. No external parasites observed. A couple of large round worms were found in the lower gut, which seem to be associated with a large quantity of fecal material (hair observed). Gut contents were collected and frozen. Mike Rochford and I identified two black rats (Rattus rattus) in the remains collected from the lower gut. The stomach was empty, and a very small amount of unidentified material was collected from the esophagus (also frozen). The carcass was retained (frozen) as a specimen for the FLMNH. Photos were taken by me and by Ms. Nulman (she will email her photos). In general, another rather unremarkable young male Burmese python shows up in Paradise.

column2: Skip Snow Everglades National Park
column25: Florida Museum of Natural History Herpetology Collection
column27: Skip Snow, National Park Service, personal communication
column69: Everglades National Park, Paurotis Pond
column153: Matt Brien, University of Florida, stopped by Paurotis Pond on the evening of 20 May at 8pm after a survey of croc nesting in the park and witnessed a large alligator (9ft) surface in the middle of the pond with what turned out to be a bloated (and very stinky) python in its mouth, around 9-10ft in length. The gator swam over to the mangroves and began smashing the python around in an attempt to break it into edible portion sizes. Observation only. Nothing recovered. Photos by Matt Brien.
